# Presentation Screen Rules

## Structure
- Never use helper methods that return widgets. Build UI inline or extract it into a widget file.
- One class per file. The only allowed exception is the paired `_<ScreenName>Content` widget that lives with its screen wrapper.
- Never keep extra private widgets in the same file besides `_<ScreenName>Content`.
- Keep every screen file under 200 lines when possible. If it grows, extract reusable parts into `presentation/widgets/`.

## Screen Responsibilities
- All `BlocProvider`, bloc event dispatching, `BlocBuilder`, `BlocListener`, `BlocConsumer`, `context.watch`, and `context.select` usage must stay in the screen file.
- Screens may coordinate UI state and navigation only. Do not place business logic, data shaping, validation rules, or domain decisions in screens.
- Prefer `context.select` or `context.watch` when a small piece of state is consumed directly after `build()` instead of wrapping that area with a builder.

```dart
// ✅ GOOD
@override
Widget build(BuildContext context) {
  final title = context.select((ExampleBloc bloc) => bloc.state.title);
  return ExampleView(title: title);
}
```

## UI Composition
- Never hardcode user-visible text, colors, or asset paths in screens.
- Use `context.l10n` for text, `context.colorScheme` for colors, and project asset accessors such as `context.assets`.
- Input fields must not use `TextEditingController`. Input state lives in BLoC, screens dispatch change events, and UI reads current value and validation from state.
- Reuse default spacing constants when they already exist. Do not repeat hardcoded spacing values.
- Prefer shared components from `lib/src/components/` such as base buttons, dialogs, sheets, and other project primitives before creating custom UI.
- Prefer concise APIs like `EdgeInsets.all()` or `EdgeInsets.symmetric()` when all involved insets are the same.
- Use `Stack` only for truly layered UI. Do not use it to manually position ordinary layouts that should be solved with regular layout widgets.

## State And Status
- Prefer `state_status` extensions from `lib/src/core/bloc/state_status.dart` instead of manual status comparisons when they cover the use case.
